# Int. Bill Graham Civic Auditorium - December 9, 1968.

An auditorium filled with people perplexed by a man on a stage with unfamiliar objects.

@ Douglas Englebart
> If in your office, you as an intellectual worker were supplied with a computer display, backed up by a computer that was alive for you all day, and was instantly responsive to every action you had—how much value could you derive from that?

Doug smirks.

@ Douglas Englebart
> We're going to do our best to show you, rather than tell you about this program.

^ Cut and Remixed and Spliced with Computer History Archives

# Int. Computer History Museum - April 10, 2025

@ Ty
> The Agenda for this session is as follows.

> 1. A speed run of hyptertext
> 2. A brainstorm of user experience challenges
> 3. A live coded proof of concept of the most interesting possibility

> Before we begin, let's start with the finale, our call to action.

> We need a Hypertext Marketplace

> Every operating system has a marketplace

Apple: App Store, Windows and Xbox: Microsoft Store, PlayStation Store, Nintendo e-Shop, debian (apt), arch (yay, pacman), fedora (rpm)

> Other programming languages have package registries

javascript (npm, yarn, jsr), python (pip), ruby (gem), java (maven/gradle), rust (cargo), go (go mod), perl (cpan), .net (NuGet), dart (pub), elixir (mix)

> Hypertext has been generally been controlled in this order: by browser vendors, extension authors, library maintainers, end-users

By collapsing the complexity of creating and distributing hypertext then vendors, authors, maintainers and users can become singular every day people, like you.

@ Ty
> Let's script the future together, starting now. But first, a speed run of hypertext.

# What is Hypertext and why?

Hypertext is an interactive media format, originally designed for augmenting human memory retrieval, inspired by a hypothetical World War II era device, a "Memex"; MEMory EXpansion.

Modern hypertext is primarily known as the implementation that powers the World Wide Web.

Hypertext, the vision, exists beyond the one widely-adopted example of the web and can be better described as an infinitely fold-able pop-up book.

# Basic Hypertext

When you read hypertext, you can drill into words and concepts to uncover more knowledge and understanding of any topic that has been encoded as hypertext.

